{"title_page": "Istanbul 2461", "text_new": "{{Infobox artifact\n| name              = Istanbul #2461\n| image             = A Love Song of Shu-Sin (Shu-Suen B) \u2013 Istanbul 2461.jpg\n| image_caption     = \"The Oldest Love Poem\" (L.2461) on display at the Istanbul Museum of the Ancient Orient\n| material          = [[terracotta]]\n| size              = 10.7 x 6 x 3.1 cm<ref name=\"lost\"/>\n| writing           = [[Sumerian language]] in [[cuneiform script]]<ref name=\"lost\"/>\n| created           = 2037-2029 BC ([[Chronology of the ancient Near East|long chronology]]) <br/>1972-1964 BC (short chronology)\n| discovered_place  = [[Nippur]]\n| discovered_coords = \n| discovered_date   = late 1880s\n| discovered_by     = \n| location          = [[\u0130stanbul Archaeology Museums|Istanbul Museum of the Ancient Orient]]\n| id                = \n| map               = \n| website           = \n}}\n'''Istanbul #2461''' (also '''Ni 2461'''<ref name=\"lost\"/>, '''L.2461''') is an ancient [[Sumerian literature|Sumerian]] [[Cuneiform script|cuneiform]] [[Clay tablet|tablet]] which is believed to contain the oldest love poem ever found.<ref name=\"guinness\">[http://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/world-records/oldest-love-poem Oldest love poem] \u2013 Guinness World Records.</ref><ref name=\"nyt06\"/> It is on display at the [[\u0130stanbul Archaeology Museums|Istanbul Museum of the Ancient Orient]] (Mesopotamia Hall).<ref name=\"nyt06\"/>\n\n== Discovery ==\nThe tablet was unearthed at [[Nippur]], in lower [[Mesopotamia]] (modern day [[Iraq]]). It was one of several thousand Sumerian tablets found by archeologists during excavations between 1889 and 1900.<ref name=\"lost\">{{cite book|last1=Fant|first1=Clyde E.|last2=Reddish|first2=Mitchell G.|title=Lost Treasures of the Bible: Understanding the Bible Through Archaeological Artifacts in World Museums|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Dj6zVQJz7zYC&pg=PA247&lpg=PA247&dq=Cuneiform+tablets+of+istanbul+2461&source=bl&ots=h2TAIBl3T3&sig=o4TjIfGjrWDv8Fke7vXwho_Uog8&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwio7-qys5HYAhWMto8KHZv5Arg4ChDoAQgvMAE#v=onepage&q=Cuneiform%20tablets%20of%20istanbul%202461&f=false|date=2008-10-15|publisher=Wm. B. Eerdmans Publishing|isbn=9780802828811}}</ref>\n\nThe tablet was identified among 74000 others and translated by [[Samuel Noah Kramer]] in 1951, during his years of studies in the Istanbul Museum.<ref name=\"nyt06\"/> Kramer was deciding what works to translate next when he found the tablet in the museum drawer. He describes the moment in his book ''History Begins at Sumer'':<ref name=\"mark\">Joshua J. Mark. [https://www.ancient.eu/article/750/the-worlds-oldest-love-poem/ The World's Oldest Love Poem (Article)] \u2013 Ancient History Encyclopedia. 13 August 2014.</ref>\n{{quote|The little tablet numbered 2461 was lying in one of the drawers, surrounded by a number of other pieces. When I first laid eyes on it, its most attractive feature was its state of preservation. I soon realized that I was reading a poem, divided into a number of stanzas, which celebrated beauty and love, a joyous bride and a king named [[Shu-Sin]] \u2026 As I read it again and yet again, there was no mistaking its content. What I held in my hand was one of the oldest love songs written down by the hand of man.}}\n\n== Contents ==\nThe table contains a [[balbale]] (a kind of Sumerian poem) which is known by the titles '''\"Bridegroom, Spend the Night in Our House Till Dawn\"''' or '''\"A Love Song of Shu-Suen (Shu-Suen B)\"'''. Composed of 29 lines,<ref>The 30th line on the tablet contains a subscript: \"It is a [[balbale]] of Inana\".</ref> this poem is a monologue directed to king [[Shu-Sin]] (ruled 1972-1964 BC, [[Chronology of the ancient Near East|short chronology]], or 2037-2029 BC, long chronology<ref name=\"mark\"/>). In erotic language, the female speaker in the poem expresses her ardent desires and longings for Shu-Sin, drawing heavily on imagery related to [[honey]] and [[sweetness]].<ref name=\"lost\"/><ref>{{cite book|last1=Longman |first1=Tremper III|authorlink1=Tremper Longman|last2=Enns|first2=Peter|authorlink2=Peter Enns|title=Dictionary of the Old Testament: Wisdom, Poetry & Writings: A Compendium of Contemporary Biblical Scholarship|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kE2k36XAkv4C&lpg=PA756&dq=drawing%20heavily%20imagery%20related%20%20honey%20%20sweetness&pg=PA756#v=onepage&q=drawing%20heavily%20imagery%20related%20%20honey%20%20sweetness&f=false|date=2008-06-06|publisher=InterVarsity Press}}</ref> \n\nThe following is the start of the poem (in Kramer's translation):<ref name=\"mark\"/>\n: ''Bridegroom, dear to my heart,''\n: ''Goodly is your beauty, honeysweet,''\n: ''Lion, dear to my heart,''\n: ''Goodly is your beauty, honeysweet.''\n\nThe last three lines of the poem seem to contain an invitation to a sexual encounter, but in language not adequately clear to us.<ref name=\"lost\"/><ref name=\"context\">{{cite book|last1=Hallo|first1=William W.|authorlink1=William W. Hallo|last2=Younger|first2=K. Lawson|title=The Context of Scripture: Canonical compositions from the biblical world|url=https://rosary2007.wordpress.com/2014/12/04/canonical-compositions-from-the-biblical-world/|volume=1|year=2003|publisher=Brill}}</ref>\n\nThe text is one of the oldest known [[Lyric poetry|lyric poems]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Heffelfinger|first=Katie M.|title=Abstract: \u201cI Am Large, I Contain Multitudes\u201d: Second Isaiah\u2019s Lyric Exploration of Divine Relational and Emotional Complexity|url=https://legacy-etd.library.emory.edu/file/view/pid/emory:17qsv/etd/emory:17qrq/heffelfinger_dissertation.pdf|year=2009}}</ref>\n\n== Interpretations ==\nIt is believed that the poem is a script for the yearly [[Hieros gamos#Ancient Near East|\"sacred marriage\"]], a rite in which the king would symbolically marry the goddess [[Inanna]], mate with her, and ensure fertility and prosperity for the coming year. A priestess would probably represent Inanna, the Sumerian goddess of fertility, and the king [[Shu-Sin]] would represent [[Dumuzid the Shepherd|Dumuzi]], the god of shepherds, on the eve of their union.<ref name=\"mark\"/><ref name=\"nyt06\"/> \n\nVariants of the poem may have been sung during ritual ceremonies commemorating the divine marriage between the two gods all over the ancient [[Near East]], particularly in [[Egypt]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Price|first1=J. Randall|authorlink1=J. Randall Price|last2=House|first2=H. Wayne|title=Zondervan Handbook of Biblical Archaeology: A Book by Book Guide to Archaeological Discoveries Related to the Bible|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3xDxCgAAQBAJ&pg=PT203&lpg=PT203&dq=%22bridegroom,+spend+the+night+in+our+house+till+dawn%22&source=bl&ots=0p3XlmylB9&sig=liaWrZpW8Y7qJI2J5V3xMmY7puY&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj-mMeXupHYAhXLqI8KHZrICTEQ6AEIODAE#v=onepage&q=%22bridegroom%2C%20spend%20the%20night%20in%20our%20house%20till%20dawn%22&f=false|date=2017-11-28|publisher=Zondervan|isbn=9780310527640}}</ref><ref name=\"mark\"/> The translation of this tablet shed light on the [[Song of Songs|Song of Solomon]] in the [[Old Testament]], because some phrases are similar to the poems sung during such fertility feasts, as well as Sumerian weddings.<ref name=\"nyt06\">Sebnem Arsu. [https://www.nytimes.com/2006/02/14/world/europe/the-oldest-line-in-the-world.html The Oldest Line in the World] // The New York Times, 14-Feb-2006.</ref>\n\n== Literature ==\n* Sefati, Yitschak. \"Sumerian Canonical Compositions. A. Divine Focus. 6. Love Poems: Dumuzi-Inanna Songs (1.169)\". In ''The Context of Scripture, I: Canonical Compositions from the Biblical World.'' Hallo, William W. (ed). Leiden/New York/K\u00f6ln: Brill, 1997. 541\u2013542. <small>(title: Bridegroom, spend the night in our house till dawn)</small>\n* Sefati, Yitschak. ''Love songs in Sumerian literature: critical edition of the Dumuzi-Inanna songs.'' Bar-Ilan Studies in Near Eastern Languages and Culture. Publications of the Samuel N. Kramer Institute of Assyriology. Ramat-Gan: Bar-Ilan University Press, 1998. 353\u2013359.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* \"A love song of Shu-Suen (Shu-Suen B)\" at the [[Electronic Text Corpus of Sumerian Literature]]: [http://etcsl.orinst.ox.ac.uk/section2/tr2442.htm translation], [http://etcsl.orinst.ox.ac.uk/section2/c2442.htm composite text], [http://etcsl.orinst.ox.ac.uk/section2/b2442.htm bibliography]\n\n[[Category:21st-century BC works]]\n[[Category:20th-century BC works]]\n[[Category:Sumerian texts]]\n[[Category:Erotic poetry]]\n[[Category:Love stories]]\n[[Category:Love poems]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox artifact\n| name              = Istanbul #2461\n| image             = A Love Song of Shu-Sin (Shu-Suen B) \u2013 Istanbul 2461.jpg\n| image_caption     = \"The Oldest Love Poem\" (L.2461) on display at the Istanbul Museum of the Ancient Orient\n| material          = [[terracotta]]\n| size              = 10.7 x 6 x 3.1 cm<ref name=\"lost\"/>\n| writing           = [[Sumerian language]] in [[cuneiform script]]<ref name=\"lost\"/>\n| created           = 2037-2029 BC ([[Chronology of the ancient Near East|long chronology]]) <br/>1972-1964 BC (short chronology)\n| discovered_place  = [[Nippur]]\n| discovered_coords = \n| discovered_date   = late 1880s\n| discovered_by     = \n| location          = [[\u0130stanbul Archaeology Museums|Istanbul Museum of the Ancient Orient]]\n| id                = \n| map               = \n| website           = \n}}\n'''Istanbul #2461''' (also '''Ni 2461'''<ref name=\"lost\"/>, '''L.2461''') is an ancient [[Sumerian literature|Sumerian]] [[Cuneiform script|cuneiform]] [[Clay tablet|tablet]] which is believed to contain the oldest love poem ever found.<ref name=\"guinness\">[http://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/world-records/oldest-love-poem Oldest love poem] \u2013 Guinness World Records.</ref><ref name=\"nyt06\"/> It is on display at the [[\u0130stanbul Archaeology Museums|Istanbul Museum of the Ancient Orient]] (Mesopotamia Hall).<ref name=\"nyt06\"/>\n\n== Discovery ==\nThe tablet was unearthed at [[Nippur]], in lower [[Mesopotamia]] (modern day [[Iraq]]). It was one of several thousand Sumerian tablets found by archeologists during excavations between 1889 and 1900.<ref name=\"lost\">{{cite book|last1=Fant|first1=Clyde E.|last2=Reddish|first2=Mitchell G.|title=Lost Treasures of the Bible: Understanding the Bible Through Archaeological Artifacts in World Museums|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Dj6zVQJz7zYC&pg=PA247&lpg=PA247&dq=Cuneiform+tablets+of+istanbul+2461&source=bl&ots=h2TAIBl3T3&sig=o4TjIfGjrWDv8Fke7vXwho_Uog8&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwio7-qys5HYAhWMto8KHZv5Arg4ChDoAQgvMAE#v=onepage&q=Cuneiform%20tablets%20of%20istanbul%202461&f=false|date=2008-10-15|publisher=Wm. B. Eerdmans Publishing|isbn=9780802828811}}</ref>\n\nThe tablet was identified among 74000 others and translated by [[Samuel Noah Kramer]] in 1951, during his years of studies in the Istanbul Museum.<ref name=\"nyt06\"/> Kramer was deciding what works to translate next when he found the tablet in the museum drawer. He describes the moment in his book ''History Begins at Sumer'':<ref name=\"mark\">Joshua J. Mark. [https://www.ancient.eu/article/750/the-worlds-oldest-love-poem/ The World's Oldest Love Poem (Article)] \u2013 Ancient History Encyclopedia. 13 August 2014.</ref>\n{{quote|The little tablet numbered 2461 was lying in one of the drawers, surrounded by a number of other pieces. When I first laid eyes on it, its most attractive feature was its state of preservation. I soon realized that I was reading a poem, divided into a number of stanzas, which celebrated beauty and love, a joyous bride and a king named [[Shu-Sin]] \u2026 As I read it again and yet again, there was no mistaking its content. What I held in my hand was one of the oldest love songs written down by the hand of man.}}\n\n== Contents ==\nThe table contains a [[balbale]] (a kind of Sumerian poem) which is known by the titles '''\"Bridegroom, Spend the Night in Our House Till Dawn\"''' or '''\"A Love Song of Shu-Suen (Shu-Suen B)\"'''. Composed of 29 lines,<ref>The 30th line on the tablet contains a subscript: \"It is a [[balbale]] of Inana\".</ref> this poem is a monologue directed to king [[Shu-Sin]] (ruled 1972-1964 BC, [[Chronology of the ancient Near East|short chronology]], or 2037-2029 BC, long chronology<ref name=\"mark\"/>). In erotic language, the female speaker in the poem expresses her ardent desires and longings for Shu-Sin, drawing heavily on imagery related to [[honey]] and [[sweetness]].<ref name=\"lost\"/><ref>{{cite book|last1=Longman |first1=Tremper III|authorlink1=Tremper Longman|last2=Enns|first2=Peter|authorlink2=Peter Enns|title=Dictionary of the Old Testament: Wisdom, Poetry & Writings: A Compendium of Contemporary Biblical Scholarship|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kE2k36XAkv4C&lpg=PA756&dq=drawing%20heavily%20imagery%20related%20%20honey%20%20sweetness&pg=PA756#v=onepage&q=drawing%20heavily%20imagery%20related%20%20honey%20%20sweetness&f=false|date=2008-06-06|publisher=InterVarsity Press}}</ref> \n\nThe following is the start of the poem (in Kramer's translation):<ref name=\"mark\"/>\n: ''Bridegroom, dear to my heart,''\n: ''Goodly is your beauty, honeysweet,''\n: ''Lion, dear to my heart,''\n: ''Goodly is your beauty, honeysweet.''\n\nThe last three lines of the poem seem to contain an invitation to a sexual encounter, but in language not adequately clear to us.<ref name=\"lost\"/><ref name=\"context\">{{cite book|last1=Hallo|first1=William W.|authorlink1=William W. Hallo|last2=Younger|first2=K. Lawson|title=The Context of Scripture: Canonical compositions from the biblical world|url=https://rosary2007.wordpress.com/2014/12/04/canonical-compositions-from-the-biblical-world/|volume=1|year=2003|publisher=Brill}}</ref>\n\nThe text is one of the oldest known [[Lyric poetry|lyric poems]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Heffelfinger|first=Katie M.|title=Abstract: \u