rk Times, 14-Feb-2006.</ref>\n\n== Literature ==\n* Sefati, Yitschak. \"Sumerian Canonical Compositions. A. Divine Focus. 6. Love Poems: Dumuzi-Inanna Songs (1.169)\". In ''The Context of Scripture, I: Canonical Compositions from the Biblical World.'' Hallo, William W. (ed). Leiden/New York/K\u00f6ln: Brill, 1997. 541-542. <small>(title: Bridegroom, spend the night in our house till dawn)</small>\n* Sefati, Yitschak. ''Love songs in Sumerian literature: critical edition of the Dumuzi-Inanna songs.'' Bar-Ilan Studies in Near Eastern Languages and Culture. Publications of the Samuel N. Kramer Institute of Assyriology. Ramat-Gan: Bar-Ilan University Press, 1998. 353-359.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* \"A love song of Shu-Suen (Shu-Suen B)\" at the [[Electronic Text Corpus of Sumerian Literature]]: [http://etcsl.orinst.ox.ac.uk/section2/tr2442.htm translation], [http://etcsl.orinst.ox.ac.uk/section2/c2442.htm composite text], [http://etcsl.orinst.ox.ac.uk/section2/b2442.htm bibliography]\n\n[[Category:21st-century BC works]]\n[[Category:20th-century BC works]]\n[[Category:Sumerian texts]]\n[[Category:Erotic poetry]]\n[[Category:Love stories]]\n[[Category:Love poems]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eLiterature:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 541-542 \u2192 541\u2013542 (2)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Istanbul_2461"}
{"title_page": "Interaction Design Institute Ivrea", "text_new": "'''Interaction Design Institute Ivrea''' (also known as '''Interaction Ivrea''' or by its acronym '''IDII''') was a graduate design program in the field of [[Interaction Design]] operating in the town of [[Ivrea]], in Northern [[Italy]].\n\n==History==\nThe school director was [[Gillian Crampton Smith]],<ref>[http://www.interaction-venice.com/about-us.html interaction-venice.com]</ref>] and the school's mission was described in Blueprint <ref>{{cite news | first=Nico | last=Macdonald | title=Action, Interaction, Reaction | date=2005-04-18 | url=http://www.spy.co.uk/Articles/Blueprint/ID/ | work=Blueprint | pages=6 | accessdate=2008-09-23 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20030810184210/http://www.spy.co.uk/Articles/Blueprint/ID/ | archivedate=2003-08-10 }}</ref> as:\n:''\"While following in the spirit of the CRD<ref>CRD refers to the original Computer Related Design master course in interaction design at the [[Royal College of Art]], London. It is now called Design Interactions.</ref> course, Ivrea will explore business in addition to design and technology. Crampton Smith believes that today there is an 'art' in imagining new business models, and is also aware that, partly because of their broad education, design graduates often move into strategic roles in companies and need to be equipped to learn for themselves.\"''\n\nThe school operated from 2001<ref>{{cite news | first=Irene Maria | last=Scalise | coauthors= | title=arrivano i designer interattivi | date=2001-10-03 | publisher=Repubblica | url =http://ricerca.repubblica.it/repubblica/archivio/repubblica/2001/10/03/arrivano-designer-interattivi.html | work = | pages = | accessdate = 2008-09-23 | language = Italian }}</ref>\nto 2005,<ref>{{cite news | first= | last= | coauthors= | title=Interaction Design Institute, fuga a Milano | date=2005-04-18 | publisher= | url =http://ricerca.quotidianiespresso.it/lasentinella/archivio/lasentinella/2005/04/18/IC2PO_IC201.html | work =La Sentinella del Canavese | pages =2 | accessdate = 2008-09-23 | language = Italian }}</ref> finally merging its teaching programme with [[Domus Academy]] and subsequently ceasing operating as an independent entity when its initial 5-year endowment ran out; the new [[Telecom Italia]] ownership decided not to renew the funding. Its exhibition design unit (E1) was spun off to form an independent company, Interaction Design Lab<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.interactiondesign-lab.com/ | title=Interaction Design Lab | accessdate = 2009-10-04 }}</ref>, currently operating in Milan. Among the academic advisors of Interaction Ivrea were leading practitioners and theorists like [[John Maeda]], [[Ranjit Makkuni]], [[Joy Mountford]], [[John Thackara]], [[Bill Verplank]], Nathan Shedroff<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nathan.com/ |title=Nathan Shedroff |accessdate=2009-10-04}}</ref>, [[Bill Moggridge]] (co-founder of [[IDEO]]) and [[David Liddle]] (co-founder of [[Interval Research]]).\n\nInteraction Ivrea student work was exhibited at the Victoria and Albert's museum in London <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vam.ac.uk/vastatic/microsites/1376_touch_me/index.html |title=Touch Me |accessdate=2008-09-23 |date=2005-06-16 |publisher=Victoria and Albert's Museum }}</ref> and at Salone del Mobile in Milan. It was also part of the Convivio <ref>{{cite web |url=http://cordis.europa.eu/data/PROJ_FP5/ACTIONeqDndSESSIONeq112422005919ndDOCeq521ndTBLeqEN_PROJ.htm |archive-url=http://webarchive.loc.gov/all/20060724062818/http://cordis.europa.eu/data/PROJ_FP5/ACTIONeqDndSESSIONeq112422005919ndDOCeq521ndTBLeqEN_PROJ.htm |url-status=dead |archive-date=2006-07-24 |title=Convivio |accessdate=2008-09-23 |date=2003-01-01 |publisher=European Union }}</ref> [[Network of Excellence]] European research project.\n\nWhile the Institute also did a measure of outside consulting work and hosted visiting researchers, its main activity was the Interaction Design Master course, a 2-year course which graduated four classes of approximately 20 students each over its existence. Graduates of Interaction Ivrea now work throughout the design spectrum. The institute was involved in many projects that later became very visible in the design world: among them, the prototyping boards [[Wiring (development platform)|Wiring]] and [[Arduino]], the graphics [[software prototyping]] environment [[Processing (programming language)|Processing]] (started at the [[MIT MediaLab]]), the [[CICCIO]] [[inflatable]] environment<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.unpacked.it/ciccioproject/ |title=CICCIO Project |accessdate=2012-10-14}}</ref>  and the Interaction Design Primer design manual.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.postmediabooks.it/29idprimer/idprimer.htm |title=Interaction Design Primer |accessdate=2008-10-28 |date=2005-01-01 |publisher=Postmedia Books |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080922185516/http://www.postmediabooks.it/29idprimer/idprimer.htm |archivedate=2008-09-22 }}</ref> Ivrea alumni and ex-faculty now work in places like [[Nuova Accademia di Belle Arti|NABA]], [[Domus Academy, Postgraduate School of Design|Domus Academy]], [[IDEO]], [https://www.ixds.com/ IXDS], [[Universit\u00e0 Iuav di Venezia]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iuav.it/Facolta/facolt--di1/ |title=Universit\u00e0 IUAV di Venezia |accessdate=2008-10-28 |date=2003-01-01 |publisher=IUAV}}</ref> [[Virginia Commonwealth University|VCU]], the [[Delft University of Technology]], [https://web.archive.org/web/20160227031853/http://www.fh-potsdam.de/studieren/design/studiengaenge/interfacedesign/ University of Applied Sciences Potsdam], and fashion company [[CuteCircuit]]. Interaction Design Institute Ivrea alumni and former staff members set up the [[Copenhagen Institute of Interaction Design]] in 2006.\n\nA partial archive of Interaction-Ivrea's website can be found at http://interactionivrea.org/en/index.asp\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n{{coord missing|Italy}}\n\n[[Category:Design schools]]\n[[Category:Higher education in Italy]]\n[[Category:Ivrea]]\n[[Category:Arduino]]\n", "text_old": "'''Interaction Design Institute Ivrea''' (also known as '''Interaction Ivrea''' or by its acronym '''IDII''') was a graduate design program in the field of [[Interaction Design]] operating in the town of [[Ivrea]], in Northern [[Italy]].\n\n==History==\nThe school director was [[Gillian Crampton Smith]],<ref>[http://www.interaction-venice.com/about-us.html interaction-venice.com]</ref>] and the school's mission was described in Blueprint <ref>{{cite news | first=Nico | last=Macdonald | title=Action, Interaction, Reaction | date=2005-04-18 | url=http://www.spy.co.uk/Articles/Blueprint/ID/ | work=Blueprint | pages=6 | accessdate=2008-09-23 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20030810184210/http://www.spy.co.uk/Articles/Blueprint/ID/ | archivedate=2003-08-10 }}</ref> as:\n:''\"While following in the spirit of the CRD<ref>CRD refers to the original Computer Related Design master course in interaction design at the [[Royal College of Art]], London. It is now called Design Interactions.</ref> course, Ivrea will explore business in addition to design and technology. Crampton Smith believes that today there is an 'art' in imagining new business models, and is also aware that, partly because of their broad education, design graduates often move into strategic roles in companies and need to be equipped to learn for themselves.\"''\n\nThe school operated from 2001<ref>{{cite news | first=Irene Maria | last=Scalise | coauthors= | title=arrivano i designer interattivi | date=2001-10-03 | publisher=Repubblica | url =http://ricerca.repubblica.it/repubblica/archivio/repubblica/2001/10/03/arrivano-designer-interattivi.html | work = | pages = | accessdate = 2008-09-23 | language = Italian }}</ref>\nto 2005,<ref>{{cite news | first= | last= | coauthors= | title=Interaction Design Institute, fuga a Milano | date=2005-04-18 | publisher= | url =http://ricerca.quotidianiespresso.it/lasentinella/archivio/lasentinella/2005/04/18/IC2PO_IC201.html | work =La Sentinella del Canavese | pages =2 | accessdate = 2008-09-23 | language = Italian }}</ref> finally merging its teaching programme with [[Domus Academy]] and subsequently ceasing operating as an independent entity when its initial 5-year endowment ran out; the new [[Telecom Italia]] ownership decided not to renew the funding. Its exhibition design unit (E1) was spun off to form an independent company, {{cite web|url=http://www.interactiondesign-lab.com/ |title=Interaction Design Lab |accessdate=2009-10-04}}, currently operating in Milan. Among the academic advisors of Interaction Ivrea were leading practitioners and theorists like [[John Maeda]], [[Ranjit Makkuni]], [[Joy Mountford]], [[John Thackara]], [[Bill Verplank]], {{cite web|url=http://www.nathan.com/ |title=Nathan Shedroff |accessdate=2009-10-04}}, [[Bill Moggridge]] (co-founder of [[IDEO]]) and [[David Liddle]] (co-founder of [[Interval Research]]).\n\nInteraction Ivrea student work was exhibited at the Victoria and Albert's museum in London <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vam.ac.uk/vastatic/microsites/1376_touch_me/index.html |title=Touch Me |accessdate=2008-09-23 |date=2005-06-16 |publisher=Victoria and Albert's Museum }}</ref> and at Salone del Mobile in Milan. It was also part of the Convivio <ref>{{cite web |url=http://cordis.europa.eu/data/PROJ_FP5/ACTIONeqDndSESSIONeq112422005919ndDOCeq521ndTBLeqEN_PROJ.htm |archive-url=http://webarchive.loc.gov/all/20060724062818/http://cordis.europa.eu/data/PROJ_FP5/ACTIONeqDndSESSIONeq112422005919ndDOCeq521ndTBLeqEN_PROJ.htm |url-status=dead |archive-date=2006-07-24 |title=Convivio |accessdate=2008-09-23 |date=2003-01-01 |publisher=European Union }}</ref> [[Network of Excellence]] European research project.\n\nWhile the Institute also did a measure of outside consulting work and hosted visiting researchers, its main activity was the Interaction Design Master course, a 2-year course which graduated four classes of approximately 20 students each over its existence. Graduates of Interaction Ivrea now work throughout the design spectrum. The institute was involved in many projects that later became very visible in the design world: among them, the prototyping boards [[Wiring (development platform)|Wiring]] and [[Arduino]], the graphics [[software prototyping]] environment [[Processing (programming language)|Processing]] (started at the [[MIT MediaLab]]), the [[CICCIO]] [[inflatable]] environment<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.unpacked.it/ciccioproject/ |title=CICCIO Project |accessdate=2012-10-14}}</ref>  and the Interaction Design Primer design manual.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.postmediabooks.it/29idprimer/idprimer.htm |title=Interaction Design Primer |accessdate=2008-10-28 |date=2005-01-01 |publisher=Postmedia Books |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080922185516/http://www.postmediabooks.it/29idprimer/idprimer.htm |archivedate=2008-09-22 }}</ref> Ivrea alumni and ex-faculty now work in places like [[Nuova Accademia di Belle Arti|NABA]], [[Domus Academy, Postgraduate School of Design|Domus Academy]], [[IDEO]], [https://www.ixds.com/ IXDS], [[Universit\u00e0 Iuav di Venezia]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iuav.it/Facolta/facolt--di1/ |title=Universit\u00e0 IUAV di Venezia |accessdate=2008-10-28 |date=2003-01-01 |publisher=IUAV}}</ref> [[Virginia Commonwealth University|VCU]], the [[Delft University of Technology]], [https://web.archive.org/web/20160227031853/http://www.fh-potsdam.de/studieren/design/studiengaenge/interfacedesign/ University of Applied Sciences Potsdam], and fashion company [[CuteCircuit]]. Interaction Design Institute Ivrea alumni and former staff members set up the [[Copenhagen Institute of Interaction Design]] in 2006.\n\nA partial archive of Interaction-Ivrea's website can be found at http://interactionivrea.org/en/index.asp\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n{{coord missing|Italy}}\n\n[[Category:Design schools]]\n[[Category:Higher education in Italy]]\n[[Category:Ivrea]]\n[[Category:Arduino]]\n", "name_user": "DaOurZ", "label": "safe", "comment": "update some links", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Interaction_Design_Institute_Ivrea"}
{"title_page": "Syllable (computing)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2019|cs1-dates=y}}\nIn computing, a '''syllable''' is a name for a platform-dependent '''unit''' of '''information storage'''. Depending on the target hardware, various [[bit width]]s (and sometimes internal groupings) are associated with it. Commonly used in the 1960s and 1970s, the term has mostly fallen into disuse in favour of terms like [[byte]] or [[word (computer architecture)|word]].\n\nExamples:\n\n* {{anchor|3-bit}}[[3-bit]] syllables: some experimental [[Complex Instruction Set Computing|CISC]] designs<ref name=\"Jones_2016_CISC\"/><ref name=\"Jones_1988_CISC\"/>\n* {{anchor|8-bit}}[[8-bit]] syllables: [[English Electric KDF9]] (represented as [[syllabic octal]]s in this context) and [[Burroughs large systems]] (see also: [[Burroughs B6x00-7x00 instruction set]])\n* {{anchor|12-bit}}[[12-bit]] syllables: NCR computers such as the [[NCR 315]]<ref name=\"Schneider_1970\"/> (also called [[slab (unit)|slab]]s in this context)<ref name=\"Schneider_1970\"/><ref name=\"NCR_315_EDPS\"/><ref name=\"Bardin_1963\"/> and [[Burroughs large systems]]\n* {{anchor|13-bit}}[[13-bit]] syllables: [[Saturn Launch Vehicle Digital Computer]] (LVDC)<ref name=\"Burkey_2009_LVDC\"/> and [[Gemini Spacecraft On-Board Computer]] (OBC)<ref name=\"Burkey_2010_Gemini\"/>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Byte]]\n* [[Catena (computing)]]\n* [[Instruction syllable]]\n* [[Nibble]]\n* [[Opcode]]\n* [[Opstring]]\n* [[Parcel (computing)]]\n* [[Syllable (linguistics)]]\n* [[Word (computer architecture)]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|refs=\n<ref name=\"Jones_2016_CISC\">{{cite web |title=A Minimal CISC |work=Computer Architecture On-Line Collection |author-first=Douglas W. |author-last=Jones |publisher=[[The University of Iowa]], Department of Computer Science |date=2016 |orig-year=2012 |location=Iowa City, USA |url=http://homepage.cs.uiowa.edu/~jones/arch/cisc/ |access-date=2016-05-28 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.